				\begin{document}$$\omega _i S_i S_j$$\end{document}ωiSiSj. The result of such an interaction is determined by the relative positions of the two attitudes in the attitude spectrum and whether or not opinion amplification occurs. Amplification, which was introduced in our earlier work on opinion dynamics (Baumgaertner et al. 2016, 2018), provides a mechanism by which individuals gain confidence in their opinion when they encounter like-minded individuals. Opinion amplification is the tendency to entrench or increase the strength of an opinion when interacting with other like-minded individuals. The inclusion of amplification in our model is motivated by studies of related biases, including biased assimilation and confirmation bias (Lord et al. 1979; Miller et al. 1993; Munro et al. 2002; Taber and Lodge 2006; Jonas et al. 2001; Wason 1960, 1968). The underlying idea is that one’s current opinion biases revisions of that opinion by differentially weighting consistent and contrary information (relative to the opinion).

